ame_user": "Carsten R D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aarhus_Cathedral"}
{"title_page": "Abdul-Malik Abu", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Abdul-Malik Abu\n| image  =  File:Abdul-Malik Abu (cropped).jpg\n| image_size =  \n| caption =  Abu playing for NC State\n| position = [[Power Forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 8 \n| weight_lbs = 240\n| league = [[Liga Portuguesa de Basquetebol|Portuguese League]]\n| team = [[Sporting CP (basketball)|Sporting CP]]\n| number =6\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|9|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| high_school = *[[Marblehead High School|Marblehead]]<br/>([[Boston, Massachusetts]])\n*[[Kimball Union Academy]]<br/>([[Meriden, New Hampshire]])\n| college = [[NC State Wolfpack men's basketball|NC State]] (2014\u20132018)\n| draft_year=2018\n| years1          = 2018\u20132019\n| years2=2019\u2013present\n| team1           = [[KK Vrijednosnice Osijek|Vrijednosnice Osijek]]\n| team2=[[Sporting CP (basketball)|Sporting CP]]\n| highlights = \n}}\n'''Abdul-Malik Abu''' (born September 16, 1995), is an American professional basketball player currently playing for [[Sporting CP (basketball)|Sporting CP]] in the [[Liga Portuguesa de Basquetebol|Portuguese League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Abduk-Malik Abu Profile|url=https://www.sporting.pt/pt/modalidades/basquetebol/seniores-masculinos/plantel/abdul-malik-abu|website=Sporting CP|accessdate=15 January 2020|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nAbu first attended [[Marblehead High School]] in [[Marblehead, Massachusetts]] before transferred to [[Kimball Union Academy]] in [[Meriden, New Hampshire]] to play for coach Mike Olson. As a senior, he averaged 24.5 points and 10.5 rebounds per game while leading Kimball to a (61-21) overall record and was named NEPSAC Player of the year in 2014.\n\nConsidered a four-star recruit, Abu was ranked 32nd in the ESPN 100 for the class of 2014. On September 7, 2013, Abu committed to [[NC State University]] to play college basketball.<ref>{{cite web|title=Abduk-Malik Abu Profile|url=https://www.zerozero.pt/player.php?id=737537|website=zerozero|accessdate=15 January 2020|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\nAbu spent his college career playing for the [[NC State Wolfpack]] in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC). As a freshman in 2014-2015, Abu averaged 6.4 points and 4.7 rebounds per game. As a sophomore, Abu became the starting Power Forward for the Wolfpack, where he finished second in scoring for NC State after averaging 12.9 points per game and 8.8 rebounds per game ranking fifth in the ACC for rebounds. As a junior, Abu became the focal point for a young Wolfpack team that featured incoming freshman's [[Dennis Smith Jr.]], [[Omer Yurtseven]], and Markell Johnson. On November 11, 2016, Abu recorded 15 points and 11 rebounds in an 81-79 win against [[Georgia Southern University|Georgia Southern]]. On the season, Abu averaged, 11.8 [[points per game]] and 7.0 rebounds per game, while shooting 52.9% from the field and 71.1% at the foul line.<ref name=\"globe\">{{cite web|last=Whitmer|first=Michael|title=Abdul-Malik Abu went from Hyde Park youth league to N.C. State|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2015/03/26/state-abdul-malik-abu-looking-soar-east-regional-semifinal/EmNKKU75y4Tiz8DQpawjJN/story.html|website=The Boston Globe|date=27 March 2015|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn September 2018, Abu signed for [[KK Vrijednosnice Osijek|Vrijednosnice Osijek]] of the [[Croatian Basketball League|Croatian League]] and [[Alpe Adria Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Abdul Malik Abu, novi je igra\u010d Vrijednosnica Osijek|url=https://kkvrijednosniceosijek.hr/abdul-malik-abu-novi-je-igrac-vrijednosnica-osijek/|website=KK Vrijednosnice Osijek |date=20 September 2018|accessdate=13 January 2019|language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Abu signed for [[Sporting CP (basketball)|Sporting CP]], a team of the [[Liga Portuguesa de Basquetebol|Portuguese League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Abdul-Malik Abu \u00e9 Le\u00e3o|url=https://www.sporting.pt/pt/noticias/modalidades/basquetebol/2019-08-19/abdul-malik-abu-e-leao|website=Sporting CP |date=19 August 2019|accessdate=19 August 2019|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAbu is a devout Muslim and prays multiple times a day.<ref name=\"globe\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.draftexpress.com/profile/Abdul-Malik-Abu-71689/ DraftExpress profile]\n* [http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/3138158/abdul-malik-abu ESPN profile]\n* [http://gopack.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3313 NC State bio]\n* [https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Abdul-Malik-Abu/Summary/52541 RealGM profile]\n* [https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/abdul-malik-abu-1.html Sports Reference profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abu, Abdul-Malik}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:NC State Wolfpack men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Sporting CP basketball players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Boston]]\n[[Category:American Muslims]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n\n\n{{1990s-US-basketball-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Abdul-Malik Abu\n| image  =  File:Abdul-Malik Abu (cropped).jpg\n| image_size =  \n| caption =  Abu playing for NC State\n| position = [[Power Forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 8 \n| weight_lbs = 240\n| league = [[Liga Portuguesa de Basquetebol|Portuguese League]]\n| team = [[Sporting CP (basketball)|Sporting CP]]\n| number =6\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|9|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| high_school = *[[Marblehead High School|Marblehead]]<br/>([[Boston, Massachusetts]])\n*[[Kimball Union Academy]]<br/>([[Meriden, New Hampshire]])\n| college = [[NC State Wolfpack men's basketball|NC State]] (2014\u20132018)\n| draft_year=2018\n| years1          = 2018\u20132019\n| years2=2019\u2013present\n| team1           = [[KK Vrijednosnice Osijek|Vrijednosnice Osijek]]\n| team2=[[Sporting CP (basketball)|Sporting CP]]\n| highlights = \n}}\n'''Abdul-Malik Abu''' (born September 16, 1995), is an American professional basketball player currently playing for [[Sporting CP (basketball)|Sporting CP]] in the [[Liga Portuguesa de Basquetebol|Portuguese League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Abduk-Malik Abu Profile|url=https://www.sporting.pt/pt/modalidades/basquetebol/seniores-masculinos/plantel/abdul-malik-abu|website=Sporting CP|accessdate=15 January 2020|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nAbu first attended [[Marblehead High School]] in [[Marblehead, Massachusetts]] before transferred to [[Kimball Union Academy]] in [[Meriden, New Hampshire]] to play for coach Mike Olson. As a senior, he averaged 24.5 points and 10.5 rebounds per game while leading Kimball to a (61-21) overall record and was named NEPSAC Player of the year in 2014.\n\nConsidered a four-star recruit, Abu was ranked 32nd in the ESPN 100 for the class of 2014. On September 7, 2013, Abu committed to [[NC State University]] to play college basketball.<ref>{{cite web|title=Abduk-Malik Abu Profile|url=https://www.zerozero.pt/player.php?id=737537|website=zerozero|accessdate=15 January 2020|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\nAbu spent his college career playing for the [[NC State Wolfpack]] in the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC). As a freshman in 2014-2015, Abu averaged 6.4 points and 4.7 rebounds per game. As a sophomore, Abu became the starting Power Forward for the Wolfpack, where he finished second in scoring for NC State after averaging 12.9 points per game and 8.8 rebounds per game ranking fifth in the ACC for rebounds. As a junior, Abu became the focal point for a young Wolfpack team that featured incoming freshman's [[Dennis Smith Jr.]], [[Omer Yurtseven]], and Markell Johnson. On November 11, 2016, Abu recorded 15 points and 11 rebounds in an 81-79 win against [[Georgia Southern University|Georgia Southern]]. On the season, Abu averaged, 11.8 [[points per game]] and 7.0 rebounds per game, while shooting 52.9% from the field and 71.1% at the foul line.<ref name=\"globe\">{{cite web|last=Whitmer|first=Michael|title=Abdul-Malik Abu went from Hyde Park youth league to N.C. State|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2015/03/26/state-abdul-malik-abu-looking-soar-east-regional-semifinal/EmNKKU75y4Tiz8DQpawjJN/story.html|website=The Boston Globe|date=27 March 2015|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn September 2018, Abu signed for [[KK Vrijednosnice Osijek|Vrijednosnice Osijek]] of the [[Croatian Basketball League|Croatian League]] and [[Alpe Adria Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Abdul Malik Abu, novi je igra\u010d Vrijednosnica Osijek|url=https://kkvrijednosniceosijek.hr/abdul-malik-abu-novi-je-igrac-vrijednosnica-osijek/|website=KK Vrijednosnice Osijek |date=20 September 2018|accessdate=13 January 2019|language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Abu signed for [[Sporting CP (basketball)|Sporting CP]], a team of the [[Liga Portuguesa de Basquetebol|Portuguese League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Abdul-Malik Abu \u00e9 Le\u00e3o|url=https://www.sporting.pt/pt/noticias/modalidades/basquetebol/2019-08-19/abdul-malik-abu-e-leao|website=Sporting CP |date=19 August 2019|accessdate=19 August 2019|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAbu is a devout Muslim and prays multiple times a day.<ref name=\"globe\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.draftexpress.com/profile/Abdul-Malik-Abu-71689/ DraftExpress profile]\n* [http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/3138158/abdul-malik-abu ESPN profile]\n* [htt