ences==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Dumbarton F.C. seasons}}\n{{1877\u201378 in Scottish football}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dumbarton}}\n[[Category:Dumbarton F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:Scottish football clubs 1877\u201378 season]]\n[[Category:1877\u201378 in Scottish football]]\n", "name_user": "Aitkegs", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1877%E2%80%9378_Dumbarton_F.C._season"}
{"title_page": "World Mind Sports Games", "text_new": "\n\nThe '''World Mind Sports Games''' ('''WMSG''') is a quadrennial [[multi-sport event]] created by the [[International Mind Sports Association]] (IMSA) as a \"stepping stone on the path of introducing a third kind of [[Olympic Games]] (after the Summer and the Winter Olympics)\".<ref>[http://www.worldbridge.org/competitions/worldchampionships/worldbridgegames.asp World Bridge Games]. World Bridge Federation. Retrieved 2011-05-27.</ref>\n\nThe inaugural [[2008 World Mind Sports Games]] were held in Beijing from October 3 to 18, about two months after the [[2008 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] and one month after the [[2008 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]].<ref name=0xin/><ref name=0pak/><ref name=bbc/> Five [[mind sports]] participated in the first Games: [[Contract Bridge|bridge]], [[chess]], [[draughts]] (checkers), [[Go (board game)|go]] (weiqi), and [[xiangqi]] (Chinese chess).<ref name=0fide/><ref name=0chess/> Thirty-five gold medals were contested by 2,763 competitors from 143 countries.<ref>[http://www.2008wmsg.org/2008-wmsg-results \"2008 WMSG Results\"]. 2008WMSG. Retrieved 2011-05-25.</ref>\n\nThe second WMSG were held in [[Lille]], [[France]] from August 9 to 23, 2012, starting during the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] and ending shortly before the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]].\n\nIn September 2016, the relevant bridge events were run as the [[World Bridge Games]] in [[Wroc\u0142aw]], Poland.<ref>http://worldbridge.org/world-bridge-games.aspx</ref>\n\n==Related events==\n\nIn addition to the quadrennial WMSG, the [[International Mind Sports Association]] also organises the [[SportAccord World Mind Games]], whose \"first annual\" edition was held in Beijing, December 2011. The SportAccord Games have fewer and smaller events with cash prizes.<ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/site/news_full/22.html \"Great Success of the 2011 SportAccord World Mind Games\"]. News (no date). IMSA. Retrieved 2012-06-04.</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nAt the first two WMSG events, medals were contested in five different [[mind sport|mind sports]]: [[contract bridge|bridge]], [[chess]], [[draughts]] (checkers), [[go (game)|go]] (weiqi), and [[xiangqi]] (Chinese chess).<ref name=0fide/><ref name=0chess/><ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/uploads/pdf/Presentation_2012.pdf \"2nd World Mind Sports Games: Lille 2012\"] (pdf presentation). IMSA. Retrieved 2012-06-04.</ref> The [[International Federation of Poker]] (IFP) is an observer member of IMSA, so [[poker]] has been mentioned as a possible future sport at the WMSG. Mathematical games are also planned to be present at 2012 WMSG, in the form of a contest between national teams. The [[Mahjong International League]] was accepted as the sixth member of IMSA in 2017.<ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/wp/mahjong/mah-jong-now-a-full-member-of-imsa/ Mah Jong now a full member of IMSA]. IMSA. Retrieved 2017-06-05.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''WMSG Sports'''\n! Number !! Sport !! Organisation !! Web !! Join\n|-\n|  align=center|1 || [[Chess]] || [[FIDE|World Chess Federation]] || http://www.fide.com/ || 2008\n|- \n|  align=center|2 || [[draughts|Draughts]] ||[[World Draughts Federation]] || https://fmjd.org/ || 2008\n|-\n|  align=center|3 || [[Go (game)|Go]] || [[International Go Federation]] || http://www.intergofed.org/ || 2008\n|- \n|  align=center|4 || [[Xiangqi]] || [[World Xiangqi Federation]] || http://www.wxf.org/ || 2008\n|-\n|  align=center|5 || [[Contract bridge|Bridge]] || [[World Bridge Federation]] || http://www.worldbridge.org/ || 2008\n|-\n|  align=center|6 || [[Poker]] || [[International Federation of Poker]] || http://pokerfed.org/ || 2010 *\n|-\n|  align=center|7 || [[Mahjong]] || [[Mahjong International League]] || http://mahjong-mil.org/ || 2017\n|-\n|  align=center|8 || [[Card game]] || [[Federation of Card Games]] || http://www.fcgoffical.com/ || 2018\n|}\n* Provisional\n\n==Continuing competitions==\nMore than half of the 2008 participants were bridge players, partly because the [[World Bridge Federation]] transferred some important quadrennial competitions to the WMSG, especially the Open and Women flights of its [[World Team Olympiad]].<ref group=lower-alpha>The third flight, contesting the Senior International Cup, also moved as a non-medal event sharing the same venues.</ref> In 2004 there had been in the main continuing events 72 Open and 43 Women \"Olympiad\" entries (national {{gcb|teams-of-four}} with six players on most squads). Under the Minds Sports rubric in Beijing there were 71 and 54 entries, about 700 players. The one-time, similar tournament with a 28 years age limit attracted another 400 players.\n\n==Editions==\nThe third edition of the games was originally planned to take place in Brazil. It was then moved to Baku, and then to Macau. It will no longer be held in 2016, but might take place in 2017. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://senseis.xmp.net/?WorldMindSportsGames|title=World Mind Sports Games at Sensei's Library|author=|date=|website=senseis.xmp.net|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''WMSG Hosts'''\n! Number !! Year !! City !! Dates !! Events\n|-\n| align=center|1 ||[[2008 World Mind Sports Games|2008]] || {{flagicon|China}} [[Beijing]], [[China]] || 3\u201318 October || align=center|35\n|- \n| align=center|2 ||[[2012 World Mind Sports Games|2012]] ||  {{flagicon|France}} [[Lille]], [[France]] || 9\u201323 August || align=center|30\n|}\n\nThe Games were originally intended to convene sometime after the Summer Olympics (and Paralympics)<!-- do they follow the Summer OG directly? --> in the same city or at least the same country, using some of the same facilities. The inaugural Games did use the Olympic Village in [[Beijing]] about two months after the Olympics and one month after the Paralympics. However, this intention was not carried out in 2012, as [[Lille]] was chosen as host of the WMSG for the year that the Summer Olympics were held in [[London]], [[Great Britain]].\n\nFor 2016, the Olympic host [[Brazil]] early on expressed an interest in hosting the third WMSG.<ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/site/news_full/19.html \"The Brazilian Mind Sport Association is founded: Brazil becomes a candidate to host the World Mind Sports Games in 2016\"]. News (no date). IMSA. Retrieved 2012-06-04.</ref> At the closing ceremony of the 2012 games, [[Rio de Janeiro]] was indeed announced as hosts for the 2016 event,<ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/IMSA_bul_14_color.pdf] Retrieved 2012-10-03.</ref> but as of May 2016 postponement until 2017 looks likely.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mind sport]]\n* [[Mind Sports Olympiad]]\n* [[International Mind Sports Association]]\n* [[SportAccord World Mind Games]]\n* [[World Team Olympiad]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist |group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<!-- TO DO\n   learn how to combine column-count= and refs=\n   learn how to combine single and double quotation marks, in effect\n   decide which refs should continue to be cited here, which at split articles, which deleted\n -->\n<ref name=bbc>\n[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/7651145.stm \"Beijing hosts first ^Mind Games^\"]. Shirong Chen. [[BBC]] News, 3 October 2008. Retrieved 2011-03-23.</ref>\n<!--\n   nicknames begin with 0 (zero) for these oldest refs (4) http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=World_Mind_Sports_Games&diff=208997251&oldid=208995068\n -->\n<ref name=0xin>\n[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-09/26/content_6795421.htm \"First World Mind Sports Games to be held in Beijing\"]. www.chinaview.cn 26 September 2007. Retrieved 2008-04-29.</ref>\n<ref name=0pak>\n[http://www.thenews.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=90855 \"China to host Bridge Games\"] The News\u2013International, Pakistan. Retrieved 2008-04-29.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928200306/http://www.thenews.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=90855 |date=September 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n<ref name=0fide>\n[http://www.fide.com/component/content/article/4-tournaments/2900-the-first-international-mind-sports-games-imsa-cup \"The first international mind sports games ^IMSA Cup^\"]. [[FIDE]] (chess) 22 April 2008. Retrieved 2008-04-29.</ref>\n<ref name=0chess>\n[http://latestchess.com/showNews.php?id=146 \"China to host 1st World Mind Sports Games\"]. latestchess.com 4 March 2008. Retrieved 2008-04-29.</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.imsaworld.com/ International Mind Sports Association] official website.\n\n{{World Mind Sports Games}}\n{{Multi-sport events}}\n{{WPCBIndex}}\n\n[[Category:World Mind Sports Games| ]]\n[[Category:Multi-sport events]]\n[[Category:Mind sports competitions]]\n[[Category:Contract bridge world competitions]]\n", "text_old": "\n\nThe '''World Mind Sports Games''' ('''WMSG''') is a quadrennial [[multi-sport event]] created by the [[International Mind Sports Association]] (IMSA) as a \"stepping stone on the path of introducing a third kind of [[Olympic Games]] (after the Summer and the Winter Olympics)\".<ref>[http://www.worldbridge.org/competitions/worldchampionships/worldbridgegames.asp World Bridge Games]. World Bridge Federation. Retrieved 2011-05-27.</ref>\n\nThe inaugural [[2008 World Mind Sports Games]] were held in Beijing from October 3 to 18, about two months after the [[2008 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] and one month after the [[2008 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]].<ref name=0xin/><ref name=0pak/><ref name=bbc/> Five [[mind sports]] participated in the first Games: [[Contract Bridge|bridge]], [[chess]], [[draughts]] (checkers), [[Go (board game)|go]] (weiqi), and [[xiangqi]] (Chinese chess).<ref name=0fide/><ref name=0chess/> Thirty-five gold medals were contested by 2,763 competitors from 143 countries.<ref>[http://www.2008wmsg.org/2008-wmsg-results \"2008 WMSG Results\"]. 2008WMSG. Retrieved 2011-05-25.</ref>\n\nThe second WMSG were held in [[Lille]], [[France]] from August 9 to 23, 2012, starting during the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] and ending shortly before the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]].\n\nIn September 2016, the relevant bridge events were run as the [[World Bridge Games]] in [[Wroc\u0142aw]], Poland.<ref>http://worldbridge.org/world-bridge-games.aspx</ref>\n\n==Related events==\n\nIn addition to the quadrennial WMSG, the [[International Mind Sports Association]] also organises the [[SportAccord World Mind Games]], whose \"first annual\" edition was held in Beijing, December 2011. The SportAccord Games have fewer and smaller events with cash prizes.<ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/site/news_full/22.html \"Great Success of the 2011 SportAccord World Mind Games\"]. News (no date). IMSA. Retrieved 2012-06-04.</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nAt the first two WMSG events, medals were contested in five different [[mind sports]]: [[Contract Bridge|bridge]], [[chess]], [[draughts]] (checkers), [[Go (board game)|go]] (weiqi), and [[xiangqi]] (Chinese chess).<ref name=0fide/><ref name=0chess/><ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/uploads/pdf/Presentation_2012.pdf \"2nd World Mind Sports Games: Lille 2012\"] (pdf presentation). IMSA. Retrieved 2012-06-04.</ref> The [[International Federation of Poker]] (IFP) is an observer member of IMSA, so [[poker]] has been mentioned as a possible future sport at the WMSG. Mathematical games are also planned to be present at 2012 WMSG, in the form of a contest between national teams. The [[Mahjong International League]] was accepted as the sixth member of IMSA in 2017.<ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/wp/mahjong/mah-jong-now-a-full-member-of-imsa/ Mah Jong now a full member of IMSA]. IMSA. Retrieved 2017-06-05.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''WMSG Sports'''\n! Number !! Sport !! Organisation !! Web !! Join\n|-\n|  align=center|1 || [[Chess]] || [[FIDE|World Chess Federation]] || http://www.fide.com/ || 2008\n|- \n|  align=center|2 || [[draughts|Draughts]] ||[[World Draughts Federation]] || https://fmjd.org/ || 2008\n|-\n|  align=center|3 || [[Go (game)|Go]] || [[International Go Federation]] || http://www.intergofed.org/ || 2008\n|- \n|  align=center|4 || [[Xiangqi]] || [[World Xiangqi Federation]] || http://www.wxf.org/ || 2008\n|-\n|  align=center|5 || [[Contract bridge|Bridge]] || [[World Bridge Federation]] || http://www.worldbridge.org/ || 2008\n|-\n|  align=center|6 || [[Poker]] || [[International Federation of Poker]] || http://pokerfed.org/ || 2010 *\n|-\n|  align=center|7 || [[Mahjong]] || [[Mahjong International League]] || http://mahjong-mil.org/ || 2017\n|-\n|  align=center|8 || [[Card game]] || [[Federation of Card Games]] || http://www.fcgoffical.com/ || 2018\n|}\n* Provisional\n\n==Continuing competitions==\nMore than half of the 2008 participants were bridge players, partly because the [[World Bridge Federation]] transferred some important quadrennial competitions to the WMSG, especially the Open and Women flights of its [[World Team Olympiad]].<ref group=lower-alpha>The third flight, contesting the Senior International Cup, also moved as a non-medal event sharing the same venues.</ref> In 2004 there had been in the main continuing events 72 Open and 43 Women \"Olympiad\" entries (national {{gcb|teams-of-four}} with six players on most squads). Under the Minds Sports rubric in Beijing there were 71 and 54 entries, about 700 players. The one-time, similar tournament with a 28 years age limit attracted another 400 players.\n\n==Editions==\nThe third edition of the games was originally planned to take place in Brazil. It was then moved to Baku, and then to Macau. It will no longer be held in 2016, but might take place in 2017. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://senseis.xmp.net/?WorldMindSportsGames|title=World Mind Sports Games at Sensei's Library|author=|date=|website=senseis.xmp.net|accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''WMSG Hosts'''\n! Number !! Year !! City !! Dates !! Events\n|-\n| align=center|1 ||[[2008 World Mind Sports Games|2008]] || {{flagicon|China}} [[Beijing]], [[China]] || 3\u201318 October || align=center|35\n|- \n| align=center|2 ||[[2012 World Mind Sports Games|2012]] ||  {{flagicon|France}} [[Lille]], [[France]] || 9\u201323 August || align=center|30\n|}\n\nThe Games were originally intended to convene sometime after the Summer Olympics (and Paralympics)<!-- do they follow the Summer OG directly? --> in the same city or at least the same country, using some of the same facilities. The inaugural Games did use the Olympic Village in [[Beijing]] about two months after the Olympics and one month after the Paralympics. However, this intention was not carried out in 2012, as [[Lille]] was chosen as host of the WMSG for the year that the Summer Olympics were held in [[London]], [[Great Britain]].\n\nFor 2016, the Olympic host [[Brazil]] early on expressed an interest in hosting the third WMSG.<ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/site/news_full/19.html \"The Brazilian Mind Sport Association is founded: Brazil becomes a candidate to host the World Mind Sports Games in 2016\"]. News (no date). IMSA. Retrieved 2012-06-04.</ref> At the closing ceremony of the 2012 games, [[Rio de Janeiro]] was indeed announced as hosts for the 2016 event,<ref>[http://www.imsaworld.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/IMSA_bul_14_color.pdf] Retrieved 2012-10-03.</ref> but as of May 2016 postponement until 2017 looks likely.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mind sport]]\n* [[Mind Sports Olympiad]]\n* [[International Mind Sports Association]]\n* [[SportAccord World Mind Games]]\n* [[World Team Olympiad]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist |group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<!-- TO DO\n   learn how to combine column-count= and refs=\n   learn how to combine single and double quotation marks, in effect\n   decide which refs should continue to be cited here, which at split articles, which deleted\n -->\n<ref name=bbc>\n[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/7651145.stm \"Beijing hosts first ^Mind Games^\"]. Shirong Chen. [[BBC]] News, 3 October 2008. Retrieved 2011-03-23.</ref>\n<!--\n   nicknames begin with 0 (zero) for these oldest refs (4) http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=World_Mind_Sports_Games&diff=208997251&oldid=208995068\n -->\n<ref name=0xin>\n[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-09/26/content_6795421.htm \"First World Mind Sports Games to be held in Beijing\"]. www.chinaview.cn 26 September 2007. Retrieved 2008-04-29.</ref>\n<ref name=0pak>\n[http://www.thenews.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=90855 \"China to host Bridge Games\"] The News\u2013International, Pakistan. Retrieved 2008-04-29.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928200306/http://www.thenews.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=90855 |date=September 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n<ref name=0fide>\n[http://www.fide.com/component/content/article/4-tournaments/2900-the-first-international-mind-sports-games-imsa-cup \"The first international mind sports games ^IMSA Cup^\"]. [[FIDE]] (chess) 22 April 2008. Retrieved 2008-04-29.</ref>\n<ref name=0chess>\n[http://latestchess.com/showNews.php?id=146 \"China to host 1st World Mind Sports Games\"]. latestchess.com 4 March 2008. Retrieved 2008-04-29.</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.imsaworld.com/ International Mind Sports Association] official website.\n\n{{World Mind Sports Games}}\n{{Multi-sport events}}\n{{WPCBIndex}}\n\n[[Category:World Mind Sports Games| ]]\n[[Category:Multi-sport events]]\n[[Category:Mind sports competitions]]\n[[Category:Contract bridge world competitions]]\n", "name_user": "Kenwick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Mind_Sports_Games"}
{"title_page": "George Mbwando", "text_new": "{{short description|Zimbabwean footballer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = George Mbwando\n| fullname       = George Stanley Mbwando\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1975|10|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    =\n| height         = 1.88 m\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub    =\n| clubnumber     =\n| youthyears1    = {{0|0000}}\u20131996\n| youthclubs1    = [[Motor Action F.C.|Blackpool FC Harare]]\n| years1         = 1996\u20131997\n| clubs1         = [[Lech Pozna\u0144]]\n| caps1          =\n| goals1         =\n| years2         = 1997\n| clubs2         = Jumbo Giants\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 1998\n| clubs3         = [[Bonner SC]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| years4         = 1998\u20131999\n| clubs4         = [[VfB Oldenburg]]\n| caps4          =\n| goals4         =\n| years5         = 2000\u20132002\n| clubs5         = [[VfB L\u00fcbeck]]\n| caps5          = 59\n| goals5         = 14\n| years6         = 2002\u20132004\n| clubs6         = [[Alemannia Aachen]]\n| caps6          = 55\n| goals6         = 4\n| years7         = 2004\u20132006\n| clubs7         = [[SSV Jahn Regensburg|Jahn Regensburg]]\n| caps7          = 41\n| goals7         = 2\n| years8         = 2006\u20132008\n| clubs8         = [[FC Ingolstadt 04|FC Ingolstadt]]\n| caps8          = 8\n| goals8         = 0\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1  = [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 11\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''George Stanley Mbwando''' (born 20 October 1975) is a Zimbabwean former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/2bundesliga/vereine/2-bundesliga/2003-04/alemannia-aachen-110/23225/spieler_george-mbwando.html | title = Mbwando, George | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate = 11 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was a member of the Zimbabwean [[2004 African Cup of Nations]] team, who finished bottom of their group in the first round of competition, thus failing to secure qualification for the quarter-finals. He also participated at the [[2006 Africa Cup of Nations]], with the same outcome.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NFT|7383}}\n\n{{Zimbabwe Squad 2004 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Zimbabwe Squad 2006 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mbwando, George}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwe international footballers]]\n[[Category:Motor Action F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lech Pozna\u0144 players]]\n[[Category:Bonner SC players]]\n[[Category:VfB Oldenburg players]]\n[[Category:VfB L\u00fcbeck players]]\n[[Category:Alemannia Aachen players]]\n[[Category:SSV Jahn Regensburg players]]\n[[Category:FC Ingolstadt 04 players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:2004 African Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2006 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Poland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean expatriate sportspeople in Poland]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n\n\n{{Zimbabwe-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Zimbabwean footballer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = George Mbwando\n| fullname       = George Stanley Mbwando\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1975|10|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    =\n| height         = {{convert|1.88|m|abbr=on}}\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub    =\n| clubnumber     =\n| youthyears1    = {{0|0000}}\u20131996\n| youthclubs1    = [[Motor Action F.C.|Blackpool FC Harare]]\n| years1         = 1996\u20131997\n| clubs1         = [[Lech Pozna\u0144]]\n| caps1          =\n| goals1         =\n| years2         = 1997\n| clubs2         = Jumbo Giants\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 1998\n| clubs3         = [[Bonner SC]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| years4         = 1998\u20131999\n| clubs4         = [[VfB Oldenburg]]\n| caps4          =\n| goals4         =\n| years5         = 2000\u20132002\n| clubs5         = [[VfB L\u00fcbeck]]\n| caps5          = 59\n| goals5         = 14\n| years6         = 2002\u20132004\n| clubs6         = [[Alemannia Aachen]]\n| caps6          = 55\n| goals6         = 4\n| years7         = 2004\u20132006\n| clubs7         = [[SSV Jahn Regensburg|Jahn Regensburg]]\n| caps7          = 41\n| goals7         = 2\n| years8         = 2006\u20132008\n| clubs8         = [[FC Ingolstadt 04|FC Ingolstadt]]\n| caps8          = 8\n| goals8         = 0\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 = [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 11\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''George Stanley Mbwando''' (born 20 October 1975) is a retired Zimbabwean [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/2bundesliga/vereine/2-bundesliga/2003-04/alemannia-aachen-110/23225/spieler_george-mbwando.html | title = Mbwando, George | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate = 11 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was a member of the Zimbabwean [[2004 African Cup of Nations]] team, who finished bottom of their group in the first round of competition, thus failing to secure qualification for the quarter-finals. He also participated at the [[2006 Africa Cup of Nations]], with the same outcome.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NFT player|pid=7383}}\n\n{{Zimbabwe Squad 2004 Africa Cup o